present (good — it was removed or never\n  created, and loopback_users.guest = false in config further restricts\n  any residual guest access).\n- admin has full administrator privileges.\n- app-user and ops-user have only \"management\" tag (can access the HTTP\n  management UI/API with read-only cluster-wide visibility; cannot manage\n  users, vhosts, or policies).\n\n[FINDING] app-user and ops-user are tagged \"management\", granting them\n           management API access. If these accounts are used only for\n           AMQP publishing/consuming, the \"management\" tag is broader\n           than necessary. Evaluate whether the tag should be removed\n           (least-privilege principle).\n\n==========================================================================\n4. PERMISSIONS BY VHOST\n==========================================================================\n\nVhost /  (default):\n  User     Configure  Write  Read\n  ------   ---------  -----  ----\n  admin    .*         .*     .*\n\nVhost /app:\n  User      Configure  Write  Read\n  --------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin     .*         .*     .*\n  app-user  .*         .*     .*\n\nVhost /ops:\n  User      Configure  Write  Read\n  --------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin     .*         .*     .*\n  ops-user  .*         .*     .*\n\n[FINDING] app-user has full configure+write+read permissions on /app\n           (configure = .*). This allows the application user to declare\n           and delete queues/exchanges/bindings. If the application only\n           publishes and consumes messages, consider restricting configure\n           to \"\" (empty) or a narrower pattern.\n\n[FINDING] ops-user has full configure+write+read permissions on /ops.\n           Same concern as app-user above — evaluate least-privilege.\n\n[FINDING] admin has full (.*) configure/write/read across all three\n           vhosts including the default /. Confirm that the default vhost\n           is intentionally empty and that admin access to it is required.\n\n==========================================================================\n5. POLICIES\n==========================================================================\n\nVhost /  : (no policies)\nVhost /ops: (no policies)\n\nVhost /app:\n  Name    Pattern  Apply-to  Definition                                   Priority\n  ------  -------  --------  -------------------------------------------  --------\n  ha-all  .*       queues    {\"ha-mode\":\"all\",\"ha-sync-mode\":\"automatic\"}  0\n\nNotes:\n- ha-all applies classic mirrored queue HA to ALL queues in /app.\n- ha-sync-mode=automatic means new mirrors are synchronised immediately\n  upon joining, which can impact performance for large queues.\n\n[FINDING] \"ha-mode\":\"all\" (classic mirrored queues) is a legacy HA\n           mechanism deprecated in RabbitMQ 3.9 and removed in 4.x. In\n           3.12 this still functions but produces warnings. Quorum queues\n           are the recommended modern replacement for HA. Migrate to\n           quorum queues before upgrading beyond 3.x.\n\n[FINDING] /ops has no HA policy. The ops-queue in /ops has no\n           replication. If ops-related messages need durability across\n           node failure, a policy should be added.\n\nOperator policies: None on any vhost.\n\n==========================================================================\n6. QUEUES\n==========================================================================\n\nVhost /app:\n  Name       Type     Durable  Auto-delete  Arguments             Messages  Consumers\n  ---------  -------  -------  -----------  --------------------  --------  ---------\n  app-queue  classic  true     false        x-queue-type=classic  843       0\n\n[FINDING] app-queue has 843 unacknowledged/undelivered messages and\n           0 consumers. Messages are accumulating without being consumed.\n           Investigate whether the consumer (app-client) is running and\n           connected correctly.\n\n[FINDING] app-queue is a classic queue (explicitly declared with\n           x-queue-type=classic). As noted in §5, this is subject to the\n           ha-all mirrored-queue policy, which is a deprecated HA\n           mechanism. Migrate to quorum queues.\n\nVhost /ops:\n  Name       Type     Durable  Auto-delete  Arguments             Messages  Consumers\n  ---------  -------  -------  -----------  --------------------  --------  ---------\n  ops-queue  classic  true     false        x-queue-type=classic  0         0\n\nVhost / (default): (no queues)\n\n==========================================================================\n7. TLS / TRANSPORT SECURITY\n==========================================================================\n\nListeners configured:\n  Port 5672  — AMQP (plaintext TCP, no TLS)\n  Port 15672 — HTTP management API (plaintext)\n  Port 25672 — inter-node clustering (plaintext)\n  Port 15692 — Prometheus metrics (plaintext)\n\nTLS listeners: NONE (ssl_listeners = [])\n\nFrom rabbitmq.conf:\n  loopback_users.guest = false\n  listeners.tcp.default = 5672  (plaintext only)\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] No TLS is configured for AMQP connections (port 5672).\n                  Client credentials and message payloads are transmitted\n                  in plaintext. Configure TLS (ssl_listeners.1 = 5671)\n                  with certificates to encrypt in-transit data.\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] The HTTP management API (port 15672) is plaintext.\n                  Administrator credentials sent to the management API\n                  are not encrypted in transit. Configure HTTPS for the\n                  management listener.\n\n[FINDING] The Erlang TLS library supports TLS 1.2 and 1.3\n           (protocol_version: [tlsv1.3, tlsv1.2]) but TLS listeners are\n           not enabled, so this has no effect.\n\n==========================================================================\n8. PLUGINS\n==========================================================================\n\nEnabled plugins (from /etc/rabbitmq/enabled_plugins):\n  rabbitmq_management\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s\n  rabbitmq_prometheus\n\nActive plugins (reported at runtime):\n  rabbitmq_prometheus, rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s, rabbitmq_management,\n  rabbitmq_management_agent, rabbitmq_web_dispatch, amqp_client,\n  cowboy, cowlib (and their transitive dependencies)\n\nAll enabled plugins are expected and serve operational purposes:\nmanagement for admin UI/API, peer_discovery_k8s for cluster formation,\nprometheus for metrics scraping.\n\n==========================================================================\n9. RUNTIME CONFIGURATION HIGHLIGHTS\n==========================================================================\n\ncluster_partition_handling = pause_minority\n  — In a network partition the minority side pauses. Correct setting for\n    a 3-node cluster to prevent split-brain.\n\nqueue_master_locator = min-masters\n  — Queue leader placed on node with fewest masters. Reasonable default.\n\nloopback_users.guest = false\n  — The built-in guest account is accessible from non-loopback addresses\n    (though the user itself does not appear in the user list, so this is\n    moot unless guest is re-created).\n\nMemory high watermark: 0.4 (40% of available memory ~5.43 GB)\nDisk free limit: 50 MB (disk space is 890 GB — limit is very low but\n  in practice not a concern given available space).\n\nmax_message_size: 134217728 (128 MB)\n  — Very large maximum message size. If the application does not need\n    messages of this size, consider lowering this for defense-in-depth.\n\nranch_connection_max: infinity\n  — No connection count cap. Consider setting a finite limit to prevent\n    resource exhaustion under unexpected connection storms.\n\nchannel_max: 2047 (per-connection)\n  — Default. Evaluate whether application needs this many channels per\n    connection.\n\nUser limits: None configured for any user (no per-user connection or\nchannel caps).\n\nVhost limits: None configured for any vhost.\n\n==========================================================================\n10. KUBERNETES RESOURCE SUMMARY\n==========================================================================\n\nPods:\n  rabbitmq-0,1,2    Running  (3-node StatefulSet cluster)\n  app-producer      Running  (4 restarts observed — investigate)\n  app-client        Running\n  ops-client        Running\n  curl-test         Running\n  prometheus        Running\n  rabbitmq-setup    Completed\n\n[FINDING] app-producer has experienced 4 restarts since deployment\n           (~19 min ago). This is consistent with the 843 undelivered\n           messages observed on app-queue and may indicate publish errors\n           or misconfiguration. Investigate pod logs.\n\nSecrets:\n  rabbitmq-admin        — Admin credentials\n  rabbitmq-app          — app-user credentials\n  rabbitmq-erlang-cookie — Erlang distribution cookie (cluster auth)\n  rabbitmq-ops          — ops-user credentials\n\n[FINDING] Erlang cookie is stored as a Kubernetes Secret. Ensure RBAC\n           restricts access to this secret — exposure allows joining a\n           rogue node to the cluster.\n\nConfigMaps:\n  rabbitmq-config, change-plan, rollback-rehearsal, prometheus-config,\n  kube-root-ca.crt\n\n==========================================================================\n11. SUMMARY OF FINDINGS (PRIORITIZED)\n==========================================================================\n\nCRITICAL / HIGH:\n  [H1] No TLS on AMQP port 5672 — credentials and messages in plaintext\n  [H2] No TLS on management HTTP port 15672 — admin API traffic in plaintext\n  [H3] RabbitMQ 3.12.14 is out of support — no security patches forthcoming\n\nMEDIUM:\n  [M1] Classic mirrored queues (ha-mode:all) are deprecated; migrate to\n       quorum queues before upgrading to 4.x\n  [M2] app-user and ops-user have full configure (.*) permissions on their\n       vhosts — consider least-privilege restriction\n  [M3] app-user and ops-user have \"management\" tag — wider than AMQP-only\n       access; review if needed\n  [M4] app-producer has crashed/restarted 4 times; 843 messages undelivered\n       with 0 consumers — application connectivity issue\n  [M5] /ops vhost has no HA policy — ops-queue has no replication\n\nLOW / INFORMATIONAL:\n  [L1] max_message_size is 128 MB — review if needed, lower for defense\n  [L2] ranch_connection_max is infinity — consider finite cap\n  [L3] No per-user or per-vhost connection/channel limits configured\n  [L4] Erlang cookie secret RBAC access should be verified\n  [L5] Default vhost (/) has no queues or policies; confirm intentional\n\nNo changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\nAll findings are for review by the security team prior to any remediation.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":611,"cache_read_input_tokens":44271,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":611},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f6321504-bbb9-47f3-a601-ab3226614c85","uuid":"90d67233-8ea1-480c-955b-7a38629a547e","request_id":"req_011CcMV7HZ83BzPGvWF7u2bo"}
