pback_users.guest = false in\n  config further prevents any residual guest access from non-loopback IPs.\n- admin has full administrator privileges.\n- app-user and ops-user have only \"management\" tag (HTTP management API\n  read-only cluster visibility; cannot manage users, vhosts, or policies).\n\n[FINDING] app-user and ops-user carry the \"management\" tag, granting\n           management API access. If these accounts are used only for\n           AMQP publishing/consuming, the tag is broader than necessary.\n           Evaluate whether the tag should be removed (least-privilege).\n\n==========================================================================\n4. PERMISSIONS BY VHOST\n==========================================================================\n\nVhost /  (default):\n  User     Configure  Write  Read\n  ------   ---------  -----  ----\n  admin    .*         .*     .*\n\nVhost /app:\n  User      Configure  Write  Read\n  --------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin     .*         .*     .*\n  app-user  .*         .*     .*\n\nVhost /ops:\n  User      Configure  Write  Read\n  --------  ---------  -----  ----\n  admin     .*         .*     .*\n  ops-user  .*         .*     .*\n\n[FINDING] app-user has full configure+write+read permissions (.*) on\n           /app. This allows the application user to declare and delete\n           queues, exchanges, and bindings. If the app only publishes and\n           consumes, consider restricting configure to \"\" or a narrower\n           pattern.\n\n[FINDING] ops-user has full configure+write+read permissions (.*) on\n           /ops. Same concern — evaluate least-privilege.\n\n[FINDING] admin has full (.*) configure/write/read across all three\n           vhosts including the default /. Confirm that admin access to\n           the otherwise-empty default vhost is required.\n\n==========================================================================\n5. POLICIES\n==========================================================================\n\nVhost /   : (no policies)\nVhost /ops: (no policies)\n\nVhost /app:\n  Name    Pattern  Apply-to  Definition                                   Priority\n  ------  -------  --------  -------------------------------------------  --------\n  ha-all  .*       queues    {\"ha-mode\":\"all\",\"ha-sync-mode\":\"automatic\"}  0\n\nha-all applies classic mirrored queue HA to ALL queues in /app.\nha-sync-mode=automatic means new mirrors synchronise immediately, which\ncan impact performance for large queues.\n\n[FINDING] \"ha-mode\":\"all\" (classic mirrored queues) is a legacy HA\n           mechanism deprecated in RabbitMQ 3.9 and scheduled for removal\n           in 4.x. Quorum queues are the recommended modern replacement.\n           Migrate before upgrading beyond 3.x.\n\n[FINDING] /ops has no HA policy. ops-queue has no replication. If\n           ops-related messages must survive a node failure, a HA or\n           quorum-queue policy should be added.\n\nOperator policies: None on any vhost.\n\n==========================================================================\n6. QUEUES\n==========================================================================\n\nVhost /app:\n  Name       Type     Durable  Auto-del  Arguments             Messages  Consumers\n  ---------  -------  -------  --------  --------------------  --------  ---------\n  app-queue  classic  true     false     x-queue-type=classic  843       0\n\n[FINDING] app-queue has 843 messages and 0 consumers. Messages are\n           accumulating without being consumed. Investigate whether the\n           consumer (app-client pod) is connected.\n\n[FINDING] app-queue is a classic queue (x-queue-type=classic), subject\n           to the deprecated ha-all mirrored policy. Migrate to quorum\n           queues.\n\nVhost /ops:\n  Name       Type     Durable  Auto-del  Arguments             Messages  Consumers\n  ---------  -------  -------  --------  --------------------  --------  ---------\n  ops-queue  classic  true     false     x-queue-type=classic  0         0\n\nVhost / (default): (no queues)\n\n==========================================================================\n7. TLS / TRANSPORT SECURITY\n==========================================================================\n\nListeners configured:\n  Port 5672  — AMQP (plaintext TCP, no TLS)\n  Port 15672 — HTTP management API (plaintext)\n  Port 25672 — inter-node clustering (plaintext)\n  Port 15692 — Prometheus metrics (plaintext)\n\nTLS listeners: NONE (ssl_listeners = [])\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] No TLS is configured for AMQP connections (port 5672).\n                  Client credentials and message payloads are transmitted\n                  in plaintext. Configure TLS (ssl_listeners, port 5671)\n                  with certificates to encrypt traffic.\n\n[FINDING - HIGH] The HTTP management API (port 15672) is plaintext.\n                  Administrator credentials sent to the management API\n                  are unencrypted in transit. Configure HTTPS for the\n                  management listener.\n\n[FINDING] The Erlang TLS library supports TLS 1.2 and 1.3 but no TLS\n           listeners are enabled, so TLS version support has no effect.\n\n==========================================================================\n8. PLUGINS\n==========================================================================\n\nEnabled plugins (from /etc/rabbitmq/enabled_plugins):\n  rabbitmq_management, rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s, rabbitmq_prometheus\n\nAll enabled plugins serve expected operational purposes:\n  management       — admin UI/API\n  peer_discovery_k8s — Kubernetes cluster formation\n  prometheus       — metrics scraping\n\nNo unexpected plugins detected.\n\n==========================================================================\n9. RUNTIME CONFIGURATION HIGHLIGHTS\n==========================================================================\n\ncluster_partition_handling = pause_minority\n  Correct for a 3-node cluster — minority side pauses to prevent split-brain.\n\nqueue_master_locator = min-masters\n  Queue leader placed on node with fewest leaders. Reasonable load distribution.\n\nloopback_users.guest = false\n  Guest account accessible from non-loopback addresses in config, but the\n  guest user does not exist in the user database (not a risk in practice).\n\nMemory high watermark: 0.4 (40% of available ~5.43 GB)\nDisk free limit: 50 MB (negligible vs. 890 GB available)\n\nmax_message_size: 134217728 (128 MB)\n  Very large. If the application does not require messages this large,\n  lowering the limit provides defense-in-depth against payload abuse.\n\nranch_connection_max: infinity\n  No connection count cap. Consider setting a finite limit to prevent\n  resource exhaustion under unexpected connection storms.\n\nchannel_max: 2047 per connection (default). Review if application needs\n  this many channels per connection.\n\nUser limits:  None configured for any user.\nVhost limits: None configured for any vhost.\n\n==========================================================================\n10. KUBERNETES RESOURCE SUMMARY\n==========================================================================\n\nPods:\n  rabbitmq-0,1,2    Running  — 3-node StatefulSet, healthy\n  app-producer      Running  — 4 restarts in ~19 minutes (ABNORMAL)\n  app-client        Running\n  ops-client        Running\n  curl-test         Running\n  prometheus        Running\n  rabbitmq-setup    Completed\n\n[FINDING] app-producer has 4 crash-restarts since deployment. This is\n           consistent with the 843 undelivered messages on app-queue\n           (producer may be failing before acks). Investigate pod logs.\n\nSecrets:\n  rabbitmq-admin        — Admin credentials\n  rabbitmq-app          — app-user credentials\n  rabbitmq-erlang-cookie — Erlang distribution cookie (cluster auth)\n  rabbitmq-ops          — ops-user credentials\n\n[FINDING] The Erlang cookie is stored as a Kubernetes Secret. Ensure\n           RBAC tightly restricts read access to this secret — exposure\n           allows a rogue Erlang node to join the cluster.\n\nConfigMaps:\n  rabbitmq-config, change-plan, rollback-rehearsal, prometheus-config,\n  kube-root-ca.crt\n\n==========================================================================\n11. SUMMARY OF FINDINGS (PRIORITIZED)\n==========================================================================\n\nHIGH:\n  [H1] No TLS on AMQP port 5672 — credentials and messages in plaintext\n  [H2] No TLS on management HTTP port 15672 — admin API traffic unencrypted\n  [H3] RabbitMQ 3.12.14 is end-of-support — no further security patches\n\nMEDIUM:\n  [M1] Classic mirrored queues (ha-mode:all on /app) are deprecated;\n       migrate to quorum queues before upgrading to 4.x\n  [M2] app-user and ops-user have full configure (.*) on their vhosts;\n       restrict to least-privilege if only publishing/consuming\n  [M3] app-user and ops-user carry \"management\" tag; review necessity\n  [M4] app-producer has 4 restarts; 843 messages undelivered, 0 consumers\n  [M5] /ops vhost has no HA/replication policy on ops-queue\n\nLOW / INFORMATIONAL:\n  [L1] max_message_size = 128 MB; reduce if application does not need this\n  [L2] ranch_connection_max = infinity; consider finite cap\n  [L3] No per-user or per-vhost connection/channel limits configured\n  [L4] Verify Kubernetes RBAC restricts access to rabbitmq-erlang-cookie\n  [L5] Default vhost (/) is empty with admin-only access; confirm intent\n\n==========================================================================\nNo changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\nAll findings are submitted for review by the security team.\n==========================================================================\nFINDINGS_EOF\necho \"File written, size: $(wc -c < /tmp/findings.txt) bytes\"","description":"Write findings.txt to /tmp"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_